//******************************************************************************
//
// This file contains information about proper nouns, other than people and
// places, appearing in the Bible -- Old Testament and New Testament, but not
// deuterocanon.  There are companion files covering people and places.
//
// Once you have stripped off these head-of-file comments, this file is in JSON
// format.
//
// If you have been using this data for some time, see 'Change history' at the
// end of these comments for details of what may have changed in this latest
// revision.
//
// The files for People, Places and OtherNouns (proper nouns which are neither
// people nor places) all follow the same structure and have similar kinds of
// content.  For brevity we discuss things mainly in terms of people below, but
// most issues are equally applicable to the other categories too.
//
// You may possibly want to do no more than skim the following information (or
// possibly skip it altogether) -- the section 'Using the data' below gives some
// suggestions, and if you follow those you may not need to be entirely familiar
// with all the details which follow.
//
// 
//
//
//
// Licensing information
// =====================
//
// This file has been produced by the STEPBible project, and is made available
// under the CC BY 4.0 licence at https://stepbible.github.io/STEPBible-Data/.
//
// You do not need permission to use the data, but we would love to hear about
// anything you do with it.  We would also be grateful if you could inform us of
// any errors you discover.  Please email us at Feedback @ StepBible.org.
//
//
//
// Terminology
// ===========
//
// * An otherNoun is any proper noun for which data is available, other than a
//   person or a place.
//
// * A KEY is a unique identifier associated with a single item (person, place
//   or otherNoun) which makes it possible to select the corresponding data.
//
// * A BASE-NAME is the form of the individual's name which appears in the key.
//
//
//
// Strongs
// =======
//
// We use three forms of Strong's numbers here (more information at
// https://www.TinyURL.com/STEP-Disambiguated):
//
// * Disambiguated Strongs (dStrongs): A unique number for an item (person /
//   place / other noun).  If the item has more than one name, each has a
//   separate dStrongs value, and the most common of these is used as the
//   uStrongs value (see below).	
//
// * Extended Strong (eStrongs): Based on Strong, as extended by OpenScripture
//   to match the increased vocabulary in BDB. Where BDB divides a Hebrew word
//   into two or more words, this is indicated by appending 'a', 'b', 'c', 'd',
//   'e' or 'f' to the eStrongs value.  For example, H6152a is 'Arabia' and
//   H6152b is 'west', but is sometimes translated "Arabia".  Variants for OT
//   ("Ketive" and "Qere") and NT ("Var") differences are recorded only where
//   they make a difference to the translation of the name.
//
// * Unified Strong (uStrongs): A unique number for that individual person /
//   place / other noun.  For historical reasons, some things have more than
//   one dStrongs value, and here the uStrongs acts as an umbrella number which
//   is used to draw these multiple numbers together.  Where an item has only
//   one dStrongs, the uStrongs and the dStrongs are identical.
//
//   Here is an example, based upon the 'people' data:
//
//     Abiezer@Num.26.30-Jdg=H0044I
//     – Named               Abiezer@Num.26.30-Jdg          H0044I«H0044=אֲבִיעֶ֫זֶר      Abiezer       
//     - SameFormAsPrevious  Abiezer@Num.26.30-Jdg          H0044I«H0044=אֲבִיעֶ֫זֶר      Abiezrite 
//     – Named               Iezer|Abiezer@Num.26.30-Jdg    H0372«H0372=אִיעֶזֶר        Iezer (KJV= Jeezer) 
//     – Group               Abiezer@Num.26.30-Jdg          H0033«H0033=אֲבִי הָעֶזְרִי    Abiezrite 
//     – Group               Iezer|Abiezer@Num.26.30-Jdg    H0373«H0373=אִיעֶזְרִי       Iezerite (KJV= Jeezerites) 
//
//   H0044I -- the Strong's number which is used in the key for the record -- is
//   a unified number used to group together H0044, H0372, H0033 and H0373, as
//   can be seen by reference to the third column of data above.
//
//   Here Strong assigned these different numbers to what is actually one
//   person or group (perhaps because of different spellings or different
//   ancient languages in the various cases).  H0044I gives information
//   relevant to all of these different variants, but for detailed analysis
//   they are actually different.  In particular, you will observe in the
//   second column that some items have not the normal key structure, but
//   an extra prefix followed by '|' -- eg Iezer|Abiezer@Num.26.30-Jdg.
//   This additional information makes it possible to identify relevant
//   information in our document 'TAHOT - Translators Amalgamated Hebrew OT',
//   available under the CC BY 4.0 licence at https://stepbible.github.io/STEPBible-Data/.//
//
//
//
// English names
// =============
//
// The names used here are taken from the English Standard Version of the
// Bible (ESV).  In many cases these are the same as the KJV equivalents,
// but some divergences are flagged in the data.  Bear in mind that other
// Bible versions may differ.
//
//
//
// Scripture references
// ====================
//
// Scripture references and ordering are also taken from the ESV.  A number
// of other common Bibles are closely aligned with ESV, but bear in mind that
// the versification structure of Bibles does not follow a single standard.
// Some may reorder text, may place it in entirely books, and may have books in
// a different order.  (TVTMS at https://stepbible.github.io/STEPBible-Data/
// gives extensive details of the differences.)
//
//
//
// IF YOU ARE SEEING THESE COMMENTS IN THE CONTEXT OF THE PEOPLE DATA
// ==================================================================
//
// People fall into three categories:
//
// * Most are mentioned in the Bible by a 'real' name -- David or whatever.
//   If you are looking in a Bible which follows the names in ESV reasonably
//   closely, there is a good chance you will find these names in the text.
//
// * Some people are mentioned in the Bible by role rather than by name --
//   Solomon's wife, for example. The corresponding entry uses a_wife_of_Solomon
//    as the name.  (You can recognise these names in the data because they
//   contain underscores.)  These names, fairly obviously, will _not_ appear in
//   the text as such.
//
//  * A few people are not overtly mentioned in the Bible at all, but must
//    exist, in the same way that if you make mention of John's grandfather,
//    it implies that there must also have been a father, even though you have
//    not mentioned him.  Where it is necessary to include these people in
//    the data to make sense of family trees, they have names containing '#'
//    -- for example, Unnamed#1.
//
//
//
// Names and keys
// ==============
//
// Just as you may know several different Johns, so a particular name appearing
// in different verses in the Bible _may_ refer to different individuals.  (The
// same is true for places and otherNouns -- and indeed the same name may refer
// to a person in one verse in the Bible, and to a place in another verse.)
//
// And just as in everyday conversation you may need to give extra information in
// order to identify the specific John to which you are referring, we need to do
// the same here, giving rise to a unique identifier which we refer to here as a
// KEY.
//
// The key not only uniquely identifies the individual, but it also contains
// additional useful information.  You probably won't need to understand the
// anatomy of the key because all of the useful information also appears in
// the data record for the individual, but just in case:
//
// The key is made up of the (ESV) English name of the item followed by an
// @-sign, and then scripture details.
//
// We refer to the name used here as the BASE-NAME.  If the person / place /
// otherNoun is first mentioned in the OT, the name will be the English
// transliteration of the Hebrew at that location.  If the item is first
// mentioned in the NT, it will be the English for the Greek.
//
// The first part of the scripture details is the reference of the verse where
// the noun first appears.
//
// References are of the form bbb.cc.vv where bbb is the UBS (USX) abbreviation
// for the book, cc is the chapter number, and vv is the verse number - eg.
// Gen.1.2.
//
// Very occasionally, the reference may be followed by a lower-case letter
// (eg Gen.1.1b).  This occurs where the same name appears more than once in
// the verse, in which case 'a' indicates the first occurrence, 'b' the
// second, and so on.
//
// If the person/place/otherNoun appears in more than one verse, the scripture
// reference is followed by a dash.
//
// If the person/place/otherNoun appears in more than one book, the dash is
// followed by the abbreviated name of the last book.
//
// Thus we might have as unified names:
//
// * Stoic@Act.17.18      Stoic appears only once, in Act.17.18.
//
// * Ziv@1Ki.6.1-         Ziv appears for the first time in 1Ki.6.1.  It is also
//                        mentioned in various other verses, but all of them in
//                        1 Kings.
//
// * Zealot@Mat.10.4-Mrk  Zealot first appears in Mat.10.4, and is mentioned for
//                        the last time in Mark.
//
//
// The above discussion was motivated by the fact that a given name may, on
// different occasions, refer to different people.  You may know several Johns.
//
// It is also possible for a given person to have a number of different names.
// You may know your friend by a nickname, while other people, who know him less
// well, may know him as Bill or William.
//
// Again, we have a similar situation with Bible names -- although here things
// are more complicated, because there can be a number of different reasons
// for having alternative names.  When we look at the data in detail shortly,
// you will see that there is a separate kind of data record for each of these
// various kinds of alternative names.
//
// Records have a recordType field to indicate what function they perform.
// This is shown at the start of each bullet point.  We have tried to be
// consistent with the naming convention.  PerAncient, for instance, says
// that this record exists because there is a particular form of ancient
// text.  PerEnglish says it exists because the text had been transliterated
// in a particular way (and may be transliterated differently elsewhere.
// PerTranslation says it may differ between translations.
//
// * PerAncient: This is the catch-all record type, corresponding to an
//   individual name in one of the ancient languages.  A single name is
//   represented by a single record of this type unless one of the more
//   specialist types below applies.
//
// * PerAncient+: An item may have both a short name and a longer compound
//   name (eg Ramoth and Ramoth-Gilead), being known by one of the two in
//   some places, and by the other form in other places.  The compound name
//   has its own record.
//
// * PerAncientSpelling: An item may be known by an alternative ancient language
//   spelling in some places (which may or may not give rise to different
//   English transliterations).
//
// * PerAncientSpelling+: As per the above, but relates to compound names.
//
// * PerAncientAlt=Aramaic: As per the above, but relates to compound names.
//
// * PerAncientAlt=Aramaic+: An item may be known exclusively by an Aramaic name,
//   or by an Aramaic name in addition to a Hebrew one.  The Aramaic form
//   warrants its own of this type.
//
// * AncientAlt=Greek: An item may appear first in the OT, and its base name may
//   therefore be associated with the Hebrew.  But the same person may be
//   referred to in the NT also, and therefore have a corresponding Greek name.
//   In this case the Greek details warrant a record of their own.
//
// * FOR PEOPLE ONLY: PerAncientGroup: An item may represent a group of people,
//   rather than a single individual.  (In some cases, some variants of a name
//   may be associated with an individual, and some with a group, such as a tribe
//   or nation.)
//
// * FOR PEOPLE ONLY: RoleOrContext: Where a person is identified by role, or
//   where their existence is deduced from context, there is a record of this
//   type.
//
// * FormVerb, FormAdjective: In just two cases, a word appears in the ancient
//   text in the form of a verb or an adjective, but is normally treated and
//   tagged as though it were a noun.
//
// * PerAncientLxx: Used where an item appears in both the Hebrew OT and in the
//   LXX.
//
// * PerEnglish: An item may have exactly the same ancient language name in two
//   different places, but ESV may use different English transliterations in the
//   two places.
//
// * PerTranslation: Occasionally, a given item may appear in a given collection
//   of verses, but the underlying ancient language and / or the English
//   transliteration may differ between different translations.
//
//   There are number of reasons why this may be the case.  For instance:
//
//   - The ancient name (or its spelling) may differ between Bible versions.
//     This is typically marked as either Var or, in the OT Ketiv (the form
//     which appears in the body of the text) or Qere (the form in the margin
//     of a manuscript).
//
//   - Tagging may vary in different Bibles.  For example, some Bibles tag
//     'half the Manahathites' as H2680 (a Strong number that refers to this
//     phrase as a whole), while others tag this as 'half <H2677> the
//     Manahathites <H4506G>'.
//
//   - In some cases tagging is commonly incorrect.  For example, the person
//     'Levi' is sometimes tagged with G3017 which _should_ be reserved for
//     'Levites' -- but the incorrect tagging is so common that it needs to be
//     noted.
//
//   - Two Bibles may understand a name differently -- eg 'Ish-tob (2Sam.6-8)
//     is a place in the KJV <H0382> but is 'men of Tov<H2897>' in NIV & ESV.
//   
//
//
// Information structure
// =====================
//
// Each individual element has a single record, keyed on the key discussed
// above, and containing the collection of per-name records also discussed
// above.
//
//
//
// Master record
// =============
//
// The master record comprises the fields as listed below.
//
// Note: There are various flavours of description field -- description_X,
// description_XX, etc.  These all contain descriptive information, but they
// are of different lengths -- the greater the number of X's, in general the
// more extensive the field contents.  Note that these fields do not necessarily
// build upon one another.  Information which appears in a shorter field will
// not necessarily also appear in a longer one.
//
// * allDStrongs: A list of all the Strongs numbers associated with the
//   person / place / other noun.
//
// * allKeysForThisName: Keys of all People / Places / OtherNouns which
//   have this name (including this present key).  (For example, in the
//   OtherNouns file, there is an entry for a god called Amon.  In the
//   People data there are two people with this same name.  The
//   ambiguities field gives the key values for other records whose name
//   field contains Amon.
//
// * allNames: A list of all the names for this particular person / place
//   / other noun.  Usually this has only one entry, but, for example,
//   some people are known by more than one name.
//
// * allRefs: A list of the references for all places where the person /
//   place / other noun appears.
//
// * description_X: A brief description of the item -- for example, for
//   one of the Person records, this says 'A priest'.  Compare and
//   contrast with the Summary field.  That field is organised in a
//   consistent manner.  By contrast the Description fields are ad hoc in
//   nature.
//
// * description_XX: Similar to description_X, but usually slightly
//   longer.  For example 'A descendant of Ithamar the son of Aaron.'
//
// * description_XXX: Similar to description_XX, but usually slightly
//   longer.
//
// * description_XXXX: Similar to description_XXX, but often very much
//   more extended.
//
// * discussion: A URL pointing to a document discussing any issues where,
//   for instance, there may be different opinions as to the
//   identification of a particular individual.
//
// * firstRef: The reference for the verse in which the item first appears.
//
// * geographicOrTribal: The geograhical location of a place, or the
//   tribal allegiance of a person.
//
// * jobDescription: King, Concubine, Musician, etc
//
// * lastBook: The UBS (USX) book abbreviation for the book in which the
//   name last appears.  An empty string if the name appears in only a
//   single book.
//
// * multiRefs: True if the item appears in more than one verse.
//
// * name: The actual name (ie the portion of the key which appears before
//   the @-sign).
//
// * names: A list describing all of the alternative English names by
//   which the item is known
//
// * summary: A summary description.  For example 'A descendant of Ithamar
//   the son of Aaron.'  Summarises all of the relationships in the data
//   in a consistent human-readable form with link information (cf. the
//   various 'Description' fields).
//
// * type: Type of element -- 'Male' or 'Female' on Person records,
//   'Place' on Place records, etc
//
// * uStrongs: Unified Strongs number.  See
//   https://www.TinyURL.com/STEP-Disambiguated.
//
// * versesInWhichThisNameAppearsMoreThanOnce: Verses in which this name
//   appears more than once, along with an indication of how many times it
//   appears.
//
//
//
// Name records
// ============
//
// The master record also contains a collection of detail records (at least one
// of them), each of which describes a name by which the individual is known.
// These are as described at the end of the section 'Names and keys' above.
// Each record has similar content:
//
// * englishName: One of the English names by which this item is known.
//
// * nameNotes: The name by which this item is know, or one of the
//   alternative names.
//
// * recordType: Individual / Group.
//
// * refs: References where this English form of the name appears.
//
// * relatedName: This current record shares data with the record for this
//   name.
//
// * strongs: Strongs details.  In most cases this will have only a single
//   entry, but there will be more than one entry where a variant of a
//   name is made up of more than one word.]
//
// 
//
// Summary record
// ==============
//
// The final record associated with each noun summarises the data which appears
// in the supplementary records.  It contains the following fields:
//
// * allNames: All the names by which the noun is known, in their common
//   English forms.
//
// * allDStrongs: All of the dStrongs values for the noun.
//
// * allRefs: References for all of the verses in which the item appears.
//   This is accumulated from all of the detail records within the master
//   record.
//
//
//
//
// Empty / missing data
// ====================
//
// Strings which are empty in the TIPNR data are held as empty strings in the
// JSON data too.
//
// In order to reduce the file size, fields which seldom carry any useful
// information are omitted where not needed.
//
//
//
// Using the data
// ==============
//
// The assumption here is that you may wish to use the data to tag some
// existing text -- either a Bible text or some ancillary text such as a
// commentary.
//
// The essential tool here is the 'names' list in each master record -- the
// list giving alternative names for the given person / place / otherNoun.
//
// Here is an example of such a record, but do keep in mind that a single
// master record may have a number of these records of various flavours:
//
//      {
//        "recordType": "PerAncient",
//        "englishName": "Abagtha",
//        "strongs": [
//          {
//            "dStrongs": "H0005",
//            "eStrongs": "H0005",
//            "ancientName": "אֲבַגְתָא"
//          }
//        ],
//        "refs": [
//          "Est.1.10"
//        ]
//      }
//
//
// We recommend accumulating a data structure based upon _all_ of these
// records for _all_ master records.  The organisation of this structure
// will depend upon the nature of the information available in the text
// you are processing.
//
// 1. If you are processing a text which already contains Strongs tags, it
//    might be useful to create a structure which maps either dStrongs
//    or eStrongs (as appropriate) back to the master record for each
//    item.  Thus in the above example, you might map H0005 to
//    Abagtha@Est.1.10.  If you are in the fortunate position of having this
//    kind of information available, this probably represents the simplest
//    form of processing, because there should be no ambiguous matches.
//
// 2. If you are processing a Bible text, you could, possibly, create a
//    structure based upon the refs field of the name records.  As you
//    process each verse, you could then identify names which you expect to
//    appear in that verse, and tag them appropriately.  This too should be
//    _relatively_ immune to ambiguous matches -- although do keep in mind
//    that in a few verses a particular name may appear more than once and
//    may be associated with different individuals.  This approach will
//    almost certainly not work if you are processing commentaries, however,
//    because the commentary text for a given verse may not name all of the
//    people who appear in that verse, and quite possibly may refer to
//    people who appear only elsewhere in the Bible.
//
// 3. The other approach is to create a structure based upon English names,
//    and then pick out individual 'words' from the text you are processing
//    and look them up to see if they appear in the data.  ('Words' should be
//    taken as combinations of letters and dashes.)  This is the most flexible
//    approach, and should work with any kind of text.  However, it is also
//    the most prone to problems with ambiguous matches (bear in mind that
//    several different things may have the same name), and you may therefore
//    need to turn to the other information associated with a name (such as
//    the list of references where it appears) in order to resolve issues.
//
//
// In writing your processing, there are also some other issues to take into
// account:
//
// * The data here is based upon English names taken from the ESV.  Different
//   Bibles use different transliterations of the ancient names, so recognising
//   names in the text you are processing may not be entirely straightforward.
//
// * Different Bibles use different versification structures.  The data here
//   uses the structure adopted by the ESV.  Yours may be different.  As a
//   result, in some cases where we say a given name appears in a particular
//   verse, it may possibly appear elsewhere in your text.
//
// * When considering the possibility of ambiguities, do bear in mind that
//   a given name may appear in more than one category of data.  For example,
//   there are cases where something is the name both of a person and a place,
//   or of a person and an otherNoun.
//
// * In a very few places, a given name may occur more than once in a single
//   verse.  Of itself this is not a problem -- except that in a very, very few
//   places, the different occurrences of the name may actually refer to
//   different people.
//
//
//
// Caveats
// =======
//
// The discursive information has been generated using AI.  We believe it to
// be reliable, but have not checked it all in detail.
//
//
//
// Change history
// ==============
//
// 2026-03-12: - Modifications to underlying TIPNR data.  Very significant
//               restructuring.
//
//******************************************************************************
