    "summary": "A monster; called <strong=\"H0930\">Behemoth</strong> (בְּהֵמוֹת)",
    "description_X": "",
    "description_XX": "A powerful, majestic creature described in the Bible",
    "description_XXX": "Behemoth, mentioned in Job.40.15, is a powerful and majestic creature that God uses to illustrate His creative power and sovereignty.",
    "description_XXXX": "Behemoth is a mysterious creature mentioned in the book of Job, specifically in chapter 40, verse 15. In this passage, God is speaking to Job and draws his attention to the Behemoth as an example of His creative power and wisdom. <p>The description of Behemoth suggests that it is a large, powerful, and majestic creature. It is said to eat grass like an ox and has immense strength in its loins and belly (Job.40.15-16). Its bones are compared to tubes of bronze and limbs like bars of iron, indicating its sturdy and robust build (Job.40.18). <p>Behemoth is described as the \"first of the works of God,\" implying that it is a prime example of God's creative abilities (Job.40.19). The passage also mentions that only its Creator can approach it with a sword, suggesting that Behemoth is not easily overcome or controlled by humans (Job.40.19). <p>The exact identity of Behemoth is uncertain, and various interpretations have been proposed. Some scholars suggest that it may refer to a hippopotamus, elephant, or even a mythical creature. However, the primary purpose of the Behemoth in the book of Job is to illustrate God's power, wisdom, and sovereignty over His creation, rather than to provide a zoological description.",
